{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478770","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478770"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:16:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:16:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18810"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18810","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18810"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.9,0.01,0.01,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11543"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79411"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11543","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11543"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18810"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64733"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"5901"},{"type":"tags","id":"11217"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27165"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27166"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79411","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79411"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of progressive leg weakness and difficulty walking. Two weeks ago, he had a gastrointestinal illness with diarrhoea that resolved spontaneously. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 105/65 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. He has symmetric weakness of both legs (power 3/5) with absent deep tendon reflexes. Upper limb power is 4/5 with reduced reflexes. Sensation is intact. Cranial nerve examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECerebrospinal fluid analysis reveals protein 0.8 g/L (0.15-0.45) with normal cell count.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Transverse myelitis","Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome","Botulism","Myasthenia gravis","Acute viral myositis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome (GBS). \u003Cstrong\u003EGuillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by ascending symmetric weakness, areflexia, and often follows a gastrointestinal or respiratory infection by 1-4 weeks. The cerebrospinal fluid shows albuminocytologic dissociation (elevated protein with normal cell count), which is characteristic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransverse myelitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with a clearly defined sensory level and bladder dysfunction, which are not present in this case. The preserved sensation and ascending pattern of weakness make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBotulism\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with descending paralysis starting with cranial nerve involvement (diplopia, ptosis, bulbar symptoms). This patient\u0027s ascending pattern and normal cranial nerve examination make botulism unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMyasthenia gravis\u003C/strong\u003E characteristically causes fluctuating weakness that worsens with activity and improves with rest. It typically affects ocular and bulbar muscles first. The pattern of ascending weakness and areflexia is not consistent with myasthenia gravis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute viral myositis\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes muscle pain and weakness during or immediately following a viral illness, often affecting the calves bilaterally. The absence of muscle pain and the presence of areflexia make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of progressive symmetric weakness, areflexia, recent gastrointestinal illness, and albuminocytologic dissociation in the CSF strongly supports the diagnosis of Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome. Treatment typically involves intravenous immunoglobulin or plasmapheresis, along with careful monitoring of respiratory function as respiratory failure can develop rapidly.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome typically presents with ascending symmetric weakness and areflexia.","Recent gastrointestinal infection and albuminocytologic dissociation in CSF are characteristic features of Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome.","Progressive symmetric weakness with areflexia in a child should prompt consideration of Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome."],"references":["Langille MM. Guillain-Barre Syndrome in Children and Adolescents. Adv Pediatr. 2023 Aug;70(1):91-103. doi: 10.1016/j.yapd.2023.04.001. Epub 2023 May 12. PMID: 37422300."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64733"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18810"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64733","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64733"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-14T12:21:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-14T12:23:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11543"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79411"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":